(ordinary-world-families
  :count 8

  (piece
    :id \"fd-01-dinner-with-a-teenager\"
    :title \"Dinner with a teenager\"
    :prose
    \"Dinner at seven. The mother has made pasta with red sauce because
that's what everybody will eat. The teenager sits down last, plate
already served, and moves the pasta around without eating for a
minute.

'How was school,' the father asks.
'Fine.'
'Anything happen?'
'No.'

The mother knows something happened. She doesn't push. The teenager
eats three bites, drinks water, and looks at his phone.

'No phone at dinner,' the father says.

The teenager puts the phone face-down on the table with more force
than necessary. Nobody says anything about it.

After dinner the mother is cleaning the pot and the teenager comes
into the kitchen for a glass of water. He stands there a minute.
Then: 'kevin got in trouble today.'

'Yeah?'

'Yeah.'

He doesn't say what for. The mother doesn't ask. She rinses the pot.
He drinks the water. He leaves. She hears his door close.

That was the whole conversation. It was more than she thought she'd
get. Some nights that's what dinner is — a moment in the kitchen after
the plates are cleared where a teenager mentions Kevin.

She smiles a little at the pot. The teenager will be okay. Not because
Kevin got in trouble instead of him — that's not the point. Because
he told her.\")

  (piece
    :id \"fd-02-thanksgiving\"
    :title \"Thanksgiving\"
    :prose
    \"There are ten of them around the table. Twelve if you count the two
cousins who are watching football in the other room. The turkey came
out a little dry because the oven was open too much. Nobody says so.

The grandmother is at the head. She's smaller than she used to be. She
gets tired earlier. But she's here. She wanted to be here.

The uncle who always talks politics is quieter this year because
somebody had a stroke last month and everybody's been thinking about
that.

The aunt who makes the sweet potatoes has outdone herself. Everyone
takes seconds.

A cousin drops a fork. Everyone laughs. The dog under the table
notices but doesn't move because he has learned that food usually
lands where he can reach it eventually.

They go around the table with what they're thankful for. It's a small
tradition. Nobody says anything grand. The grandmother says 'you.'
Just that. She looks at the family.

Then everyone eats pie. Then everyone sits. The cousins come back
from the football room and grab plates too.

It's a small holiday. Nobody made a speech. Nobody had a big fight.
Nobody left early. That's a real success, not the kind you can
photograph.\")

  (piece
    :id \"fd-03-morning-coffee\"
    :title \"Morning coffee\"
    :prose
    \"The father is up at six. He makes coffee in the same pot he's used
for twelve years. He grinds the beans, puts water in, hits the button.

While it's brewing he stands at the window. The street is empty. A
cat crosses it. A car turns the corner. The sky is going gray-blue
from the east.

He pours the coffee into a mug that his daughter made in a pottery
class in high school. It's uneven. It leans a little to the left. He
doesn't use any of the other mugs when he's alone in the kitchen.

His wife comes down at six-forty. She kisses him on the shoulder and
pours her own coffee. She uses a different mug — a plain white one
because she likes plain white.

They stand at the window together. They don't talk. He notices the
cat is back. Different cat. Or the same. He isn't sure.

'You sleep,' she asks.
'Yeah,' he says.
'Good.'

Then they sit at the small table by the window and drink their coffee
and read separately for twenty minutes. He reads the paper. She reads
a novel.

At seven the kids wake up. The morning ends. This particular quiet
is over. They will do it again tomorrow.\")

  (piece
    :id \"fd-04-a-sick-day\"
    :title \"A sick kid\"
    :prose
    \"The kid is home sick. Sore throat, low fever. Not bad enough for
the doctor but bad enough to keep him from school.

The mother is working from home. She's set the kid up on the couch
with the blanket he likes and a small tray with soup and juice. He is
watching a movie he's seen before because when he's sick he doesn't
want new things.

Every twenty minutes she comes over and puts her hand on his forehead.
The fever is holding steady. She gives him a cough drop. He complains
about the taste. She lets him have another kind.

By the afternoon he's asleep. She works quietly at the table so as
not to wake him. When he wakes he's a little better. He asks for
crackers. She brings crackers.

The father comes home at six. He puts a hand on the kid's forehead
too. He asks the mother how the fever was. She tells him. He nods.

They don't do dinner formal. The kid has more soup. The parents eat
sandwiches at the counter. They watch the kid on the couch. He's
watching the same movie again from a different scene.

At eight the mother helps the kid up the stairs. He is heavier than
he was last year. She notices. She kisses his forehead. He is
lukewarm now.

'Feel better,' she says.
'I know,' he says.

Then he falls asleep. She stands in the doorway a minute. Then she
turns off the light.\")

  (piece
    :id \"fd-05-a-cold-day\"
    :title \"The cold day\"
    :prose
    \"The temperature dropped to twelve degrees overnight. Nobody wanted
to go outside. But everybody had to.

The mother put an extra layer on the kid. Long-sleeved shirt under
the sweater. Then a coat. Then a scarf. Then a hat that the grandmother
knitted three winters ago. Then mittens because gloves are for
teenagers.

Getting to the bus stop was a project. The wind blew straight through
Adelphi and cut across their faces. The kid started crying. Not a big
cry. Just the kind of cry you do when your cheeks are freezing.

At the bus stop the mother tucked the scarf higher. She stood in
front of the kid to block the wind. The bus was three minutes late.

When it finally came the driver said 'sorry, it's the cold.' Which
was the same thing all the drivers said. The mother nodded. She got
the kid on. The kid sat by the window and put his forehead against
the glass, which was cold, but he didn't move it.

At school the mother handed the kid off to the teacher and headed
home. The wind was still cutting. She walked with her head down. By
the time she got home her ears were bright red.

She stood in the kitchen with her hat still on and drank a glass of
tap water because she was thirsty. Then she took the hat off and hung
it on the hook. The rest of the day would happen inside.\")

  (piece
    :id \"fd-06-a-body-getting-older\"
    :title \"A body getting older\"
    :prose
    \"The knee has been bothering him for eight months. Not a sudden thing.
A slow thing. Some mornings it's fine. Some mornings it's not.

He's fifty-eight. He knows what this is. He knows the fix might be
physical therapy, might be surgery, might just be that this is how
things go.

He goes to the doctor. The doctor says the imaging shows some wear.
Some inflammation. Try physical therapy first. Six weeks. See how it
goes.

He goes to physical therapy twice a week. The therapist is a woman in
her thirties. She shows him small exercises. She is patient. She
does not talk about how his knee will be like new.

After three weeks the knee is a little better. Not fixed. Better.

He asks the therapist if it will keep getting better. She says maybe.
She says maybe he will learn to work with it. Some knees you fix and
some knees you accept.

He goes home. He does the exercises. He walks less than he used to.
He notices the knee more than he used to.

His wife notices him noticing. She doesn't say anything. She knows
he doesn't want to be babied. But she knows.

This is what getting older is. It isn't dramatic. It's a knee.\")

  (piece
    :id \"fd-07-a-body-learning\"
    :title \"A body learning\"
    :prose
    \"The two-year-old has learned to walk down stairs. Not with holding.
With holding the railing, but not holding the mother's hand.

She goes slow. One foot down. Then the other foot down onto the same
step. Then one foot down. Then the other. She looks up at the mother
every third step to check that the mother is watching.

The mother is watching.

At the bottom the toddler turns around and looks up at the stairs.
Then she looks at the mother. Then she starts back up.

Up is harder than down. She stands at the bottom step and lifts her
foot. She has to lean forward. Her diaper makes it a little awkward.
She grunts.

She gets to the top. She turns around. She starts back down.

The mother has been watching for ten minutes. She hasn't moved. She
hasn't interrupted. The toddler is doing this because she wants to.
Not because anybody made her. The mother knows this is a shape of
work that a two-year-old can do only if the adult doesn't get in the
way.

Twenty minutes later the toddler has done the stairs six times. She
is done. She walks over to the couch and climbs onto it and sits.

The mother sits down next to her. She puts a hand on the toddler's
back.

'Yeah,' she says.

The toddler nods without really understanding what she's agreeing to.
Then she falls asleep.\")

  (piece
    :id \"fd-08-the-weekly-food\"
    :title \"The weekly food\"
    :prose
    \"Sundays are the shopping day for a lot of families. The father goes
because the mother handled dinner. Or the mother goes because the
father is watching football. Or they go together because that's what
they do on Sundays. It varies.

The list is always the same shape: bread, milk, eggs, coffee, some
vegetables, some fruit, one meat, one thing for the week's dinner
plan, snacks for the kids, whatever's on sale.

The store is loud on Sundays. Two-year-olds crying. Teenagers pushing
carts. Older people with lists on paper. Younger people with lists on
phones.

The person shopping thinks about money. Every week is a small
negotiation between want and need. The mangoes are three dollars
each and the kid likes them but it's a lot for a fruit. The cereal is
buy-one-get-one so you get two boxes of cereal you don't quite want.

The checkout is a small ritual. The cashier says hello. The shopper
loads the belt. The bagger — if there's a bagger — packs the bags.
Money moves. The receipt prints.

By the time you leave the store you've been in there fifty minutes
and you're tired. You loaded the bags into the car. You drove home.
You unloaded the bags. You put things away.

Then it's Sunday afternoon and you're not thinking about food again
until dinner. The rhythm holds another week.\"))
")
